observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and the management agreed to avail of the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of the PPE account of the Municipality, specifically, the following:


a. The LCE to:
Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less;

Temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee from all their regular duties to be able to complete the physical inventory of all PPEs of the LGU in due time;

Direct the Property Unit/GSO, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, to prepare a PIP containing at least the specific assignments/ duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;




b. The Inventory Committee to:

Complete the conduct of physical count of PPE based on the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Prepare and submit the RPCPPE covering all the PPEs of the LGU;



c. Property Unit/MGSO to:

Prepare, maintain and update PCs for all classes of PPE;


Prepare and submit the IIRUP using the prescribed format for all PPE found unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed; and

Work together with the OMA to reconcile the PCs with the latter’s PPELCs.


D. Accounting Unit/OMA to:

Update PPELCs for all classes of PPE as necessary in the course of reconciliation; 


Take up necessary adjusting entries based on the results of the physical count; and

Work together with the MGSO to reconcile the PPELCs with the latter’s PCs.


We recommended, and the management agreed through the:

The LCE to prioritize the implementation of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account balances and ensure that all provisions of the circular are strictly followed.

b.	The MA to:

Prepare adjusting journal entries to revert the adjustment/derecognition of unreconciled SL balances made in the accounting records to facilitate the reconciliation process and follow the required procedures before derecognizing these assets from the books of accounts;

Provide supporting documents such as proof that the road lots derecognized are not owned nor assessed as part of the LGU’s property;

Properly reconcile accounting records with the RPCRNS to establish the correct balance of the RNs account at year-end; and

Prepare and maintain SPLC for each semi-expendable property and shall be reconciled with the SPC of the GSO;


c.	Municipal GSO to:

Prepare the RegSPI, SPC, and ICS for all semi-expendable property, especially those already derecognized from the accounting records and prepare RSPI for all future issuances of semi-expendable property which shall be the basis in preparing the JEV to recognize the issuance taking into consideration the newly issued COA Circular No. 2024-006 dated March 14, 2024, the supplemental guidelines on the implementation by LGUs of COA Circular No. 2022-004;

Office of the MA and MGSO to collaborate in the reconciliation of their records and preparation and maintenance of the prescribed forms/reports/ registries for purposes of record-keeping and installation of controls over semi-expendable properties.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to ensure the compliance of the LGU with the policies and procedures on Local Roads Asset Management System by requiring the:

The ME to provide the MA and the MGSO with complete details as to description, cost segregation of road components for road projects, and all other information necessary for the proper accounting and recording of all RNs of the LGU;

Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of physical count of all RNs of the LGU and submit the Report on the Physical Count of RN System;

c. Office of the MA to:

Prepare and maintain complete subsidiary records for roads and road components for every RN;

Make proper disclosure in the Financial Statement of RN System;

d. Municipal GSO/MTO to:

Submit the Report on Local RN in order to implement and monitor the recognition of the account Local RN in the books of accounts; and

Maintain the Local Inventory and Road Map and Local RN Property Card for all roads and its components.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

Establish and implement strategies to impose collection of the receivable accounts for those who are still capable of paying;

Conduct proper disposition of dormant receivables following the Items 7.0 and 8.0 of COA Circular 2023-008;

Create an Investigation Committee to determine the cause/s of loss or destruction of documents, pinpoint the official/s and employee/s liable for such loss, and look into the absence or presence of negligence of the part of the Accountable Officer; and

Direct the MA to monitor all receivable accounts and ensure that they are collected in due time. In the event of failure to settle their accountabilities despite the demand, appropriate action shall be made either thru salary deduction or filing of appropriate cases.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the MA to:

Revise the schedule of Due to NGAs – Kalahi CIDSS and provide separate schedule for the undetermined liabilities;

Fast track in tracing the undetermined liabilities and provide details; 

After determining the liabilities, reconcile the records with other funds, and identify if these are still outstanding or already extinguished, prepare adjustments and provide details;

Review the Memorandum of Agreement of the non-moving TF accounts, if it should continue to maintain these accounts or to be dropped and return the balances to its proper funds or source agency;

Confirm and demand the collection of these receivable accounts as these balances may be used for other PPAs of the LGUs; and 

Regularly monitor the Municipality’s cash position to avoid the same incurrence in its future operations.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:

Designate an accounts officer who will be assigned to transmit demand letters, communicate with the accountable persons, determine their whereabouts, retrieve the necessary documents to update existing records, to evaluate or assess the probability of liquidation/settlement of the advances and other receivables accounts;

Direct the MA, through the designated accounts officer, to issue demand letters to all accountable persons with unliquidated cash advances or outstanding receivables;

Direct the MT to withhold the salaries and other emoluments to those officials and employees who are still in service effective immediately and apply the said withheld amounts in full satisfaction of their respective unliquidated cash advances; and

Direct the MA, if warranted, to undertake appropriate actions in filing the request for authority to write-off the receivable accounts after complying with the conditions and documentary requirements provided in COA Circular 2016-005, especially the dormant accounts.

Recommendations
